<subSubSection id="01307254336CD242EA7E5EBFF546B688" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="20D951391E6FCB71EE9BAF3DAD875793" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB65F6B998ED463E20DD1BA1672D74C1" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">
<taxonomicName id="F28071105F5F8C6F375DEB021A09B4E3" baseAuthorityName="Blackwall" baseAuthorityYear="1857" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hogna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hogna ingens" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingens">
<emphasis id="4D3BEFC428C9A0E576EE9BD45329C80D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Hogna ingens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be diagnosed from all other Madeiran 
<taxonomicName id="50BC15B56D08BB155CCE1B45B87A496F" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1885" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hogna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hogna" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1D24A7E1E195671C1DEBB27910A55E8D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Hogna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the aspect of its legs, blackish with white patches (Figs 
<figureCitation id="5A1C897487E81DDCDA17E6EC788FC944" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Photograph of H. ingens. Female specimen in the field. Photograph credit Pedro Cardoso." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1086.68015.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646993" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5D30D4B70FA663FF38342E35546A7026" captionStart="Figure 26" captionStartId="F26" captionText="Figure 26. Plate with photographs of the lateral view of the leg I for easily diagnosable species." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1086.68015.figure26" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/647006" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">26C</figureCitation>
), and additionally by its genitalia. In males, according to literature, by the inclined palea shield (
<bibRefCitation id="0E6DB502245C6B56F74DF8C16CC841F0" author="Wunderlich, J" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur Araneologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" pagination="1 - 619" refId="B76" refString="Wunderlich, J, 1992. Die Spinnen-Fauna der Makaronesischen Inseln: Taxonomie, Oekologie, Biogeographie und Evolution. Beitraege zur Araneologie 1: 1 - 619" title="Die Spinnen-Fauna der Makaronesischen Inseln: Taxonomie, Oekologie, Biogeographie und Evolution." volume="1" year="1992">Wunderlich 1992</bibRefCitation>
: 596, fig. 720f). In females, by short epigynal anterior pockets, with lateral borders divergent and anteriorly swollen median septum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F716CA6C4308740B36C7DF81E9671863" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Hogna ingens female (CRBALC 0591): A epigyne, ventral B vulva, dorsal. Abbreviations, female genitalia: H - epigynal hoods, MS - median septum, S - spermatheca. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1086.68015.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646992" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">12A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="466CACB2A3809303A731DAB26D0B8B7B" doi="10.3897/zookeys.1086.68015.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646993" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" start="Figure 13" startId="F13">
<paragraph id="74E6752CDDBCEDCC316568683AB939A6" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis id="5107BA9DF01899C491C7E619B345C3F5" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Figure 13.</emphasis>
Photograph of 
